Market layout planning using clustering algorithms¶

Instacart is an American company founded in 2012 that operates a grocery delivery and pick-up service in the United States and Canada.

The company offers its services via a website and mobile app. The service allows customers to order groceries from participating retailers with the shopping being done by a personal shopper. Orders are fulfilled and delivered by a personal shopper, who picks, packs, and delivers the order.

Instamarket orders are available in kaggle and contain information about which items were present in each order, as well as the market layout: In which aisle the item was found and what department contains each aisle.

With this data, it is possible to analyze the relations between the orders to make business strategies regarding the layout of the hypermarket:

  1. Which aisles should be grouped together in the same department?
  2. Which departments should be close to one another?
  3. For items that had no aisle assignment, to which aisle should they be sent?
  4. Which items should be displayed near the cashier counters?

In the following analysis, all these questions will be explored.

#Defining functions
def plot_dendrogram(model, **kwargs):
    '''
    Given a clustering model, plots a dendrogram.
    '''
    # Create linkage matrix and then plot the dendrogram

    # create the counts of samples under each node
    counts = np.zeros(model.children_.shape[0])
    n_samples = len(model.labels_)
    for i, merge in enumerate(model.children_):
        current_count = 0
        for child_idx in merge:
            if child_idx < n_samples:
                current_count += 1  # leaf node
            else:
                current_count += counts[child_idx - n_samples]
        counts[i] = current_count

    linkage_matrix = np.column_stack(
        [model.children_, model.distances_, counts]
    ).astype(float)

    # Plot the corresponding dendrogram
    dendrogram(linkage_matrix, **kwargs)

def cosine_similariy(v1,v2):
    '''
    Calculates cosine similarity between two arrays of values. (v1*v2)/(mod(v1)*mod(v2))

    vector1 - array with length N
    vector2 - array with length N

    '''
    mod1=np.sqrt((v1*v1).sum())
    mod2=np.sqrt((v2*v2).sum())
    dot_product=(v1*v2).sum()
    return dot_product/(mod1*mod2)
def invert_dictionary(dict_in):
    '''
    Inverts keys and values of dictionary
    '''
    return {v: k for k, v in dict_in.items()}

1. Data exploration¶

The data available in kaggle consists of:

  1. A table that contains the order id and the product id
  2. A table associating each product id to the product name and aisle id
  3. A table associating each aisle id to the aisle name and department id
  4. A table associating each department id to the department name.

By compiling all tables together, a compiled table is obtained. The table below shows a subsect of this table for order id number 10.

2. Clustering aisles - Reorganizing which aisles should be in the same department¶

The objective in this section is to compare the similarity between all the different aisles so that similar aisles are grouped together. This way it becomes much easier for customers to buy their items, as items bought together will be grouped near one another.

Two aisles are considered similar if they appear in a lot of transactions together.

Altough many different similarity measures exist, the "cosine similarity" will be used as the main metric and is discussed below. The reason why cosine similarity is the most adequate measure for this situation will also be explained.

2.1 Methodology: cosine similarity and ward linkage¶

Before calculating any metric, the data was transformed and displayed in a new format below:

Each column represents a transaction. Each row represents an aisle id (only shown until aisle 20). If the value is equal to 1, it means that a product from this aisle appeared on the transaction. As an example, for order number 5, there were products from both aisles 1 and 4.

Each row represents an aisle and each of the transactions is a property of this aisle. By comparing two rows, we are effectively comparing two aisles.

The more times both rows have a value equal to 1 (in other words, each time a transaction contains both aisles), the more similar both are to each other.

However, it is also expected that, the more times the aisle appears, the more times it will also appear with other aisles. To calculate how similar two aisles(rows) are to each other, while at the same time accounting for the fact that some aisles are much more popular than others, we use the cosine similarity:

$$cosine_{similarity}(aisle_x,aisle_y)=\frac{aisle_x*aisle_y}{\lVert aisle_x\rVert \lVert aisle_y\rVert}$$

The similarity is the vectorial product of both rows divided by their module.

Another way of visualizing the similarity between two arrays (when the arrays contain only 0s and 1s) is to use the image below:

$$cosine_{similarity}(aisle_x,aisle_y)=\frac{count(aisle_x\ \cap\ aisle_y)}{\sqrt{count(aisle_x)}*\sqrt{count(aisle_x)}}$$

So, if aisle X appeared in 200.000 transactions, aisle Y appeared in 300.000 transactions and both appeared at the same time in 50.000 transactions, then their similarity would be:

$$cosine_{similarity}(X,Y)=\frac{50.000}{\sqrt{200.000}*\sqrt{300.000}}=0.2$$

If another aisle Z appeared in 20.000 transactions and both transactions X & Y appeared 18.000 together, then the similarity would be:

$$cosine_{similarity}(X,Z)=\frac{18.000}{\sqrt{200.000}*\sqrt{20.000}}=0.28$$

This way, even though there were less transactions with both X&Z appearing than X&Y, the cosimilarity between them was higher and both aisles are expected to be grouped closer.

The cosine similarity is ideal for this application as:

  1. The data is very unbalanced: some aisles appear in much more transactions than others, so it normalizes to account for different magnitudes in scale.
  2. There are a great number of attributes (transactions) and the data is very sparse (lots of 0s): cosine similarity is much more useful in these cases when compared to other metrics (such as correlation, jaccard index, hamming distance, etc).

The cosimilarity between all combinations of 132 aisles was calculated, leading to a 132x132 cosimilarity matrix. The first 5 rows of the matrix are shown below. As expected, all items in the diagonal are equal to 1, as it is the cosimilarity of an aisle with itself.

As an example, the cosimilarity between aisles 1 and 2 was 0.0498.

    #disconsidering index 0, as there was no aisle with index 0

After arriving at the cosine similarity matrix, to obtain the distance matrix, which is used in agglomerative clustering algorithms, one must perform the operation:

$$distance_{matrix}=1-cosimilarity_{matrix}$$

With the distance matrix, we can begin the use of agglomerative clustering, a type of hierarchical clustering algorithm. It has a bottom-up approach:

  1. Each aisle forms a cluster.
  2. All clusters are compared to each other. The closest two clusters (lowest distance) are then united into a new cluster/group.
  3. Repeat until all objects are united in a single cluster. As groups begin having multiple objects inside, some distance function must be used to measure the distance between clusters (distance of a group of objects to another group of objects). This is called a linkage function, some of the possible linkages used are:
  • Single linkage: Minimum distance between two objects of compared groups.
  • Complete linkage: Maximum distance between two objects of compared groups.
  • Average linkage: Average distance between objects of compared groups.
  • Ward linkage: Aims to minimize quadratic error (intra-group variance)

All linkage methods were tested. The best results were obtained with ward linkage.

From the hierarchical analysis, some aisle placement strategies become more clear:

  1. The closest aisles should be vegetables and fruits, together with breakfast related items. Bread should also be put near other breakfast related items. (bottom grey group)
  2. Interestingly, Frozen vegan foods should be grouped with tofu and meat alternatives, indicating the presence of vegan customers (light blue group).
  3. A junk food section (top grey group) could be created: drinks, snacks, ice cream and cakes were normally bought together.
  4. Instant foods should be moved into department of frozen prepared meals (top purple group)
  5. A department of condiments/spices/seasoning could be interesting (top pink group)

Although the hierarchical clustering was very useful in finding hidden relations between the aisles, one should not base the entire strategy of the layout on the result of the algorithm. Some groups don't make much sense and would only make it difficult for customers to find what they are looking for. As examples of nonsense groups:

  1. Bottom purple group is very counterintuitive: It contains pets, household, desserts and personal care items.
  2. Personal care (11) was also split into two different distant sections: bottom green and bottom pink.

So, even though the data may point to a relation, this relation may not have a real interpretation: in the same way "correlation does not imply causation", it is possible to say "computational similarity does not imply association".

3. Assigning products with missing information to an aisle using cosimilarity¶

The dataset had a total of 1803 out of 49677 products that had no specific aisle assignment.

By using clustering analysis it is possible to assign each product to the most similar aisle. This is done using a methodology very similar to the previous items:

  1. The cosine similarity between a product id and an aisle is calculated for all missing products and all aisles.
  2. Each product is then assigned to the aisle that it had the highest similarity to.

All the missing product and respective aisles to which they were assigned are shown below.

del count_per_order

#####PART 2 - ASSIGNING OTHERS AND MISSING TO OTHER SECTION#######
if recalculate_aisle_assignment:
    #%%
    #remaking aisles so that each item in aisle "other" or "missing" is considered as a separate aisle
    aisles=complete_orders['aisle']
    products=complete_orders['product_name']
    aisle_ids=complete_orders['aisle_id']
    combined_data=np.transpose([aisles,products,aisle_ids])
    del aisles,products,aisle_ids

    remade_aisles=list(map(lambda x:x[1] if x[2] in [6,100] else x[0],combined_data))

    complete_orders['remade_aisles']=remade_aisles
    #%%
    #Obtaining all aisles and order_ids that happened together
    count_per_order2=complete_orders.groupby(['order_id','remade_aisles']).count()[['product_id']].reset_index().rename(columns={'product_id':'product'})
    count_per_order2['product']=1


    #creating new dictionary considering products as aisles. Keep original aisles (aisles 1 to 21) identification. In the dictionary: Aisle_name as key, Aisle_id as value
    aisles_custom=list(set(pd.unique(count_per_order2['remade_aisles']))-set(aisles_dict.values()))
    aisles_custom.sort()
    aisles_dict_custom=dict(zip(aisles_custom,np.arange(len(aisles_dict)+1,len(aisles_dict)+1+len(aisles_custom))))

    inverted_aisles_dict=invert_dictionary(aisles_dict)

    aisles_dict_unified={**inverted_aisles_dict, **aisles_dict_custom}

    inverted_aisles_dict_unified={v: k for k, v in aisles_dict_unified.items()}

    #Adding remade aisle ids to dataframe
    count_per_order2['aisle_id_custom']=list(map(lambda x:aisles_dict_unified[x],count_per_order2['remade_aisles']))

    #%%

    #creating a dictionary. Each key is a transaction. Each value is the list of aisles in the transaction
    orders_aisles_list=np.transpose([list(count_per_order2['order_id']),list(count_per_order2['aisle_id_custom'])])
    dict_transactions={}
    for order_id in count_per_order2['order_id']:
        dict_transactions[order_id]=[]
    for item in orders_aisles_list:
        dict_transactions[item[0]]+=[item[1]]

    del count_per_order2
    #total number of new aisles (original aisles+products with no aisle assignment)
    number_unique_aisles_custom=len(aisles_dict_unified)

    #For each transaction, check which aisles appeared together to form a matrix that will be used to calculate the cosine similarity matrix

    common_appearances_matrix=np.zeros((number_unique_aisles_custom,number_unique_aisles_custom))
    total_count=np.zeros(number_unique_aisles_custom)

    #iterating through transactions
    for transaction in dict_transactions:

        aisles_this_trans=np.array(dict_transactions[transaction])
        #we are only interested in combinations of nonmain_aisles (from "missing" and "other" groups) and main aisles (frozen, bakery,etc)
        main_aisles_transactions=aisles_this_trans[aisles_this_trans<=len(aisles_dict)]
        nonmain_aisles_transactions=aisles_this_trans[aisles_this_trans>len(aisles_dict)]

        #add to respective index in 1D array each time an aisle appeared in a transaction
        for aisle_custom_id in aisles_this_trans:
            total_count[aisle_custom_id-1]+=1
            common_appearances_matrix[aisle_custom_id-1,aisle_custom_id-1]+=1

        #add to respective index in DD array each time two aisaislesles appeared simultaneously in a transaction

        for combination in list(itertools.product(nonmain_aisles_transactions,main_aisles_transactions)):
            common_appearances_matrix[combination[0]-1,combination[1]-1]+=1
            common_appearances_matrix[combination[1]-1,combination[0]-1]+=1
    del dict_transactions
    #calculating cosine similarity between each aisle
    cosine_similarity_matrix=common_appearances_matrix.copy()
    for i in np.arange(0,len(total_count)):
        for j in np.arange(0,len(total_count)):
            if i==j:
                cosine_similarity_matrix[i][j]=1
            else:
                cosine_similarity_matrix[i][j]=cosine_similarity_matrix[i][j]/(np.sqrt(total_count[i])*np.sqrt(total_count[j]))
    del common_appearances_matrix

    #iterate through each custom aisle (items that had no aisle assignment) and get original aisle (21 original aisles) that has the highest similarity to the product.
    #The product is then assigned to this section.
    aisle_assignment=[]
    for index in np.arange(len(aisles_dict),len(aisles_dict)+len(aisles_custom)):
        cosine_sim_this_custom_aisle=cosine_similarity_matrix[index]

        max_value=0
        count=0
        for cosine_similarity in cosine_sim_this_custom_aisle:
            if cosine_similarity>max_value and cosine_similarity!=1:
                max_value=cosine_similarity
                index_selected=count
            count+=1
        aisle_assignment+=[[inverted_aisles_dict_unified[index+1], inverted_aisles_dict_unified[index_selected+1],max_value]]
    del cosine_similarity_matrix
    aisle_assignment=pd.DataFrame(aisle_assignment,columns=['Product','Aisle Assigned','Cosine Similarity'])

    #Add extra information to the aisle assignment dataframe: number of transactions the product appeared on
    item_count=complete_orders[complete_orders['department_id'].apply(lambda x: x in [2,21])].groupby(['product_name','aisle']).count()[['order_id']].reset_index().rename(columns={'order_id':'number of transactions that had item','product_name':'Product','aisle':'aisle_origin'})

    del complete_orders

    aisle_assignment=aisle_assignment.merge(item_count,on='Product').sort_values(by='Cosine Similarity',ascending=False).reset_index(drop=True)

    aisle_assignment.to_csv('../processed_data/aisle_assignment_missing.csv')
    with open('../processed_data/aisles_dict_unified.pkl','wb') as fp:
        pickle.dump(aisles_dict_unified, fp)
else:
    aisle_assignment=pd.read_csv('../processed_data/aisle_assignment_missing.csv',index_col=0)
    with open('../processed_data/aisles_dict_unified.pkl','rb') as fp:
        aisles_dict_unified=pickle.load(fp)

Ideally, the aisle assignment would also use some sort of Natural Language processing strategy to assign the items. However, as the objective of this study is to study the potential of clustering solutions, we won't dive into this approach.

From this section onwards, all analysis will consider these products in the new aisle assigned.

3. Clustering departments and optimizing marketing layout¶

In this section, similar to section 2, the departments will be clustered accordingly to the similarity between themselves. The idea is to have similar departments close to each other.

Next, based on both the department similarity and the department importance (which will be measured by number of items sold), we will draw how the supermarket should be mapped:

  • Which departments are closer to the entrance?
  • Which departments are near each other?

The data was processed to understand which departments happened in each transaction. A table with this information is shown below.

For transaction 10, for example, items from departments 4 (produce), 12 (meat seafood), 15 (canned goods), 16 (dairy eggs) and 18 (babies) were bought.

What the dendogram aboves tell us is that "dairy eggs" and "produce" should be grouped together. Next, "snacks" and "beverages" form a new group. Third, "frozen" is added next to "snacks" and "beverages".

This information will be useful when organizing the layout of the store.

3.2 Market Layout¶

To optimize the market layout, we will consider that the store consists of 18 departments, displayed on a 3x6 grid. Such as the example below.

The objective on the planning of the market layout is to improve efficiency for customers, allowing for customers to quickly fill their wanted basket. To achieve that:

  1. Similar sections should be grouped together. (based on clustering graph above)
  2. The most important sections are closer to the center and closer to the entrance. (we will use number of items bought by department as the importance metric - this criteria follows the graphs plotted in section 1, which found that produce, dairy eggs and snacks were among the most important departments.)

This is reflected in the figure above: The lower the number of the square, the more important we consider this segment and the more important sections should be placed there.

Following both rules, the following market layout is proposed:

Obs: Bulk and international were grouped together as they both had very few items and it was necessary to reduce 19 departments down to 18 to fit the 3x6 grid.

3.3 Other Market Layout strategies¶

While the design presented aims to improve customer efficiency in the market, different strategies could be used.

If for example the objective was to incentivize the customer to buy items they were not intended on buying (incentivizing impulse buying), one could model the layout to maximize walking distance in the supermarket: the most important departments would be in the back and departments with high similarity would be on opposite sides of the market.

Altough this strategy could increase impulsive buying it could also lead to lower customer satisfaction and lower number of customers in the long term.

4. Selecting products to be displayed near supermarket cashier counters¶

Finally, the last step on the market planning is to select the items that should be displayed near the cashier counters. These items are either items likely to be impulse bought or items from a section that a customer may not have passed through.

Ideally a item would be displayed near the counters if it had the following characteristics:

  1. It is a popular item.
  2. It normally is the unique item from a department in a given transaction.
  3. It has a higher similarity to other departments than its own.

Before trying to establish a metric for the three criteria, the data was processed so that useful information could be extracted:

  • How many transactions it appeared on?
  • How many transactions it was the sole product of its own department?
  • How many transactions it occured with other departments.

This information is shown below for the first three items. As an example, product 28985 of department 4:

  • Occurred in 67449 transactions.
  • Occured in 2130 transactions as the sole product of department 4.
  • Occured 65319 times with other products of department 4.
  • Occured 31617 times with products of department 1.

With this information it was then possible to calculate key metrics to reach the characteristics judged important:

  1. Popular item - number of occurrences in transactions. The higher the value the lower the rank.
  2. Unique product of department in transactions: % of time it appeared as the single item from a department. The higher the percentage the lower the rank.
  3. Higher similarity to other departments.The lower the value of the ratio, the lower the rank: $$\frac{cosine_{similarity}\ with\ own\ department}{median\ cosine_{similarity}\ with\ other\ departments}$$

All 3 metrics were calculated for each product and ranked. To account for all three metrics, a summed rank was made, which was used to select the top 100 product suggestions to go near the counters, shown in the table below.

As an example, the first suggestion, dried mango:

  • Appeared in 10150 transactions, which placed it in the 487th rank for the first criteria.
  • For the transactions it appeared, 97.5% of the time it was the only item from the "bulk department", which placed it in 235th rank for the second criteria.
  • Had a ratio of 0.7 between the cosimilarity with its own department and the median cosimilarity with the other departments, which placed it in the 383th rank for the third criteria.
  • The final rank was equal to 487+235+383=1105th. As this was the lowest rank from the final metric, the product was selected to be placed near the counters.

Interestingly, there were a lot of items from the "bulk" department, as well as bread/bakery and snacks items.
